objects.name: Turla - Carbon Emulation Plan
objects.description: The emulation plan, created by the ATT&CK Â® Evaluations team, used during Day 1 of the ATT&CK evaluations Round 5. This scenario focuses on Carbon, a second-stage backdoor and framework that targets Windows and Linux infrastructures and provides data exfiltration capabilities.

objects.name: Spearphishing Link
objects.description: In our scenario, an email containing the spearphishing link was pre-positioned in the target user's inbox.

objects.name: Malicious File
objects.description: User clicks on the downloaded executable

objects.name: Embedded Payloads
objects.description: An additional executable is embedded inside NTFVersion.exe via the Resource section
User clicks on the spearphishing link and a fake update executable is downloaded

objects.name: NTFVersion.exe
objects.description: EPIC dropper - Fake updater file that drops an embedded binary and modifies the registry for persistence

objects.name: mxs_installer.exe
objects.description: EPIC Injector - embedded inside in the Resources section of the EPIC dropper; It loads Guard DLL (embedded in its Resource section) and injects it into svchost.exe or explorer.exe depending on privilege level

objects.name: Process Injection
objects.description: NTFVersion.exe writes the EPIC Injector to the user's path (indicated by the %TEMP% environment variable) as mxs_installer.exe

objects.name: Winlogon Helper DLL
objects.description: NTFVersion.exe modifies the registry key HKCU\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Winlogon to add a Shell key value for persistence

objects.name: Obfuscated Files or Information
objects.description: EPIC's guard DLL is embedded inside the resource section of mxs_installer.exe
User logs off and back in to the system, executing the persistence mechanism

objects.name: Dynamic-link Library Injection
objects.description: mxs_installer.exe injects EPIC's Guard DLL into explorer.exe via CreateRemoteThread API

objects.name: EPIC Guard
objects.description: 2nd stage malware; Guard DLL for the EPIC implant; embedded into the Resource section of the EPIC Injector. At the user level, it searches for an internet-enabled process. Then, it loads an embedded 3rd stage payload from its Resources section and injects it into the process

objects.name: Process Discovery
objects.description: explorer.exe enumerates processes looking for internet-enabled processes via CreateToolhelp32Snapshot API

objects.name: Embedded Payloads
objects.description: the EPIC worker DLL (the EPIC payload) is embedded in the resource section of the explorer.exe's Guard DLL

objects.name: EPIC worker DLL
objects.description: 3rd stage malware; EPIC payload; It performs various discovery commands, stores the command outputs, obfuscates this information, and sends it to the C2 server via HTTP POST requests.

objects.name: Dynamic-link Library Injection
objects.description: explorer.exe injects EPIC's worker DLL into msedge.exe via CreateRemoteThread API

objects.name: Local Account
objects.description: msedge.exe enumerates all users on the local machine via NetUserEnum API

objects.name: File and Directory Discovery
objects.description: msedge.exe enumerates users' files via FindFirstFile and FindNextFile APIs

objects.name: Archive via Library
objects.description: msedge.exe bzip2 compresses the output of its discovery commands in memory

objects.name: Standard Encoding
objects.description: msedge.exe base64 encodes the bzip2 compressed data in memory

objects.name: External Proxy
objects.description: msedge.exe connects to shoppingbeach.org via a POST request

objects.name: Local Data Staging
objects.description: The output of the file enumeration is stored in a local log file

objects.name: Permission Groups Discovery: Domain Groups
objects.description: Various net group commands are executed on the local machine to find domain admins, domain computers, and domain controllers

objects.name: System Service Discovery
objects.description: tasklist is used to enumerate services hosted in each running process

objects.name: Symmetric Cryptography
objects.description: msedge.exe uses a temporary AES key to encrypt the discovery output in memory, then sends the data to the C2 server

objects.name: Asymmetric Cryptography
objects.description: The AES key, generated by msedge.exe, is RSA encrypted

objects.name: Query Registry
objects.description: cmd.exe reg queries ViperVPNSvc

objects.name: PowerShell
objects.description: PowerShell is used to verify which users can access the ViperVPNSvc service

objects.name: Services Registry Permissions Weakness
objects.description: the ViperVPNSvc service registry key is modified for privilege escalation
The service is restarted, executing the EPIC Injector (mxs_installer.exe) with SYSTEM level privileges. Using SYSTEM level privileges, EPIC injects into svchost.exe processes.

objects.name: Ingress Tool Transfer
objects.description: svchost.exe creates WinResSvc.exe in the System32 folder

objects.name: Masquerade Task or Service
objects.description: WinResSvc.exe uses filenames mressvc.dll (Loader DLL) and MSSVCCFG.dll (Orchestrator DLL) to appear benign/legitimate

objects.name: mressvc.dll
objects.description: Loader DLL; the loader executes the orchestrator DLL

objects.name: MSSVCCFG.dll
objects.description: Orchestrator DLL; injects the communications library DLL into target processes specified in the CARBON DLL configuration file. It is also responsible for executing tasks and storing the output in encrypted files for the communications library to send to the C2 server.

objects.name: Windows Service
objects.description: WinResSvc.exe creates WinResSvc service using OpenSCManager and CreateService APIs

objects.name: Modify Registry
objects.description: WinResSvc.exe modifies 2 registry keys via RegCreateKey and RegSetValue APIs

objects.name: Service Execution
objects.description: WinResSvc.exe uses StartService API to start WinSysSvc, which executes the loader DLL (mressvc.dll) under svchost.exe. mressvc.dll loads and executes the Orchestrator DLL (MSSVCCFG.dll).

objects.name: setuplst.xml
objects.description: CAST-128 encrypted configuration file

objects.name: Dynamic-link Library Injection
objects.description: svchost.exe injects the communications DLL (msxhlp.dll) into msedge.exe via CreateRemoteThread API

objects.name: Web Protocols
objects.description: msedge.exe connects to prendre-des-vacances.fr over HTTP protocol and communicates with GET and POST requests

objects.name: Asymmetric Cryptography
objects.description: msedge.exe receives RSA encrypted symmetric key

objects.name: msxhlp.dll
objects.description: communications library dll; communicates with the C2 server either through a direct C2 channel using HTTP or peer-to-peer C2 communication using named pipes

objects.name: Symmetric Cryptography
objects.description: msedge.exe receives CAST-128 encrypted tasking

objects.name: System Owner/User Discovery
objects.description: svchost.exe uses CreateProcess API to execute cmd.exe to execute whoami

objects.name: Symmetric Cryptography
objects.description: msedge.exe CAST-128 encrypts task output

objects.name: Standard Encoding
objects.description: msedge.exe base64 encodes the CAST-128 encrypted task output

objects.name: Windows Command Shell
objects.description: cmd.exe executes winsas64.bat

objects.name: Password Spraying
objects.description: winsas64.bat sprays several weak passwords against domain admin accounts. Using Frieda's plaintext password, the C:\ drive of the domain controller is successfully mounted

objects.name: File Deletion
objects.description: svchost.exe spawns cmd.exe to delete winsas64.bat

objects.name: Ingress Tool Transfer
objects.description: msedge.exe creates C:\Windows\Temp\wmimetricsq.exe

objects.name: Lateral Tool Transfer
objects.description: svchost.exe moves C:\Windows\Temp\wmimetricsq.exe to \\bannik\C$\Windows\System32

objects.name: Scheduled Task
objects.description: svchost.exe remotely enumerates, modifies, and executes a scheduled task - \Microsoft\Windows\Customer Experience Improvement Program\Consolidator - on BANNIK

objects.name: Internal Proxy
objects.description: msedge.exe uses peer-to-peer communication over a named pipe - dsnap - through the first CARBON DLL implant on HOBGOBLIN

objects.name: Domain Groups
objects.description: svchost.exe executes cmd.exe to enumerate all groups in the domain

objects.name: Remote System Discovery
objects.description: svchost.exe executes cmd.exe to enumerate the Active Directory Computers
When the scheduled task is executed, the attacker successfully moves to BANNIK, where the user has opened a browser (msedge.exe)
The attacker identifies an Apache web server and the workstation of the administrator of the Apache web server (Adalwolfa)

objects.name: terabox.exe
objects.description: Mimikatz

objects.name: OS Credential Dumping
objects.description: cmd.exe executes terabox.exe
Adalwolfa is logged in to their workstation and opens the Edge browser. Mimikatz reveals a cached NTLM hash for the admin user Adalwolfa.

objects.description: the Carbon DLL Installer is copied to Adalwolfa's workstation (KHABIBULIN). PsExec executes the CARBON DLL Installer

Adalwolfa's SSH credentials are collected and exfiltrated

objects.description: cron receives and triggers on a TCP packet containing a magic sequence of bytes

objects.description: the TCP packet payload contains data that is base64 encoded. Once decoded, the packet contains the IP address and port to connect to the listener

HTML is appended to the webpage previously edited by Adalwolfa that contains script tags to load another JavaScript file

objects.name: Discovery

The C2 server responds with a UUID for EPIC to save for future communications. Future communications with this C2 server are also bzip2 compressed and base64 encoded.
